  <!-- Section: Application Process -->
  <section id="application" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Application Process</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The D7 visa application involves applying at a Portuguese consulate in your country of residence, then completing the residence permit process after arriving in Portugal. EU citizens can skip the visa stage and apply directly for residence after registering.
    </p>

    <ComparisonTable columns={timelineColumns} rows={timelineRows} />

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mt-8 mb-3">Step-by-Step Guide</h3>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">1</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Get Your NIF (Tax Number)</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Either visit Portugal briefly to get your NIF in person (free) or hire a fiscal representative to obtain it remotely (€50-150). The NIF is required for almost everything in Portugal, including visa applications with some consulates.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">2</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Gather and Translate Documents</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Collect your criminal record certificate (apostilled), passport, financial documents, and health insurance proof. Get certified translations of non-Portuguese documents. Some consulates require translations by specific agencies.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">3</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Secure Private Health Insurance</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Obtain private health insurance valid in Portugal. Get a confirmation letter or policy document showing coverage details. Cigna Global and Allianz Care can provide visa-ready documentation.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">4</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Arrange Accommodation Proof</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">You need to show where you'll live in Portugal. This can be a rental contract, property deed, hotel booking for initial stay, or letter from someone hosting you. Long-term Airbnb bookings with host letter can work.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">5</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Apply at Portuguese Consulate</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Book an appointment at your local Portuguese consulate. Submit all documents, pay the €90 visa fee, and attend an interview (usually brief). Some consulates accept mail-in applications for D7 renewals.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">6</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Wait for Visa Processing</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Processing typically takes 2-3 months, though some consulates are faster. You may be asked for additional documents. Once approved, you'll receive a visa sticker in your passport valid for 4 months.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">7</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Arrive and Open Bank Account</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">Enter Portugal within your visa validity. Open a Portuguese bank account (needed for rent, utilities, residence permit). ActivoBank and Millennium BCP are expat-friendly options. Some digital banks like N26 also work.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">8</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Schedule AIMA Appointment</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">AIMA (formerly SEF) handles residence permits. Book your appointment as early as possible—there's currently a significant backlog (2-6 months). Your visa stamp allows legal stay while waiting. Bring all original documents plus copies.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="flex gap-4">
        <div class="flex-shrink-0 w-8 h-8 bg-primary-600 text-white rounded-full flex items-center justify-center font-bold">9</div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Receive Your Residence Card</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600">After your AIMA appointment, you'll receive a 2-year residence permit (Autorizacao de Residencia). This card allows you to live and work in Portugal and travel freely in Schengen. Apply for NHR tax status within 12 months.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-amber-50 border border-amber-200 rounded-lg p-4 mt-6">
      <p class="text-amber-800">
        <strong>AIMA backlog warning:</strong> Portugal's immigration agency (AIMA, formerly SEF) has a significant backlog as of 2024-2026. Expect 2-6 months wait for your residence permit appointment after arrival. Your visa stamp keeps you legal during this time, but plan accordingly. Book your appointment immediately upon arrival—don't wait.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

