  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Missing the NHR 12-Month Deadline</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">You must apply for Non-Habitual Resident tax status within 12 months of becoming a Portuguese tax resident. Miss this deadline and you lose 10 years of potential tax benefits. Set a calendar reminder the day you arrive. The savings can be €5,000-10,000/year or more.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating the AIMA Backlog</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Portugal's immigration agency (AIMA, formerly SEF) has a severe backlog. Don't assume you'll get your residence permit quickly. Budget 2-6 months after arrival. Book your appointment immediately upon entering Portugal—the wait starts from booking, not arrival.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Applying Without Accommodation Proof</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Portuguese consulates require proof of where you'll live. "I'll find a place when I arrive" isn't acceptable. Secure at least a short-term rental, Airbnb booking with host confirmation, or hotel reservation before applying. Long-term housing can come later.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Confusing D7 and D8 Visa Requirements</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">D7 requires ~€870/month (minimum wage). D8 requires €3,040/month. If you earn above €3,040, you can use either—D7 is often simpler. If you earn less than €3,040, D7 is your only option. Don't apply for D8 thinking it's "better" if you don't meet the threshold.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Relying Only on Savings Without Income Proof</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">While savings help, consulates prefer to see regular income. €50,000 in savings but no income stream raises questions about sustainability. Even small recurring contracts (€500/month) plus savings is stronger than savings alone. Show ongoing financial viability.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Portugal -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in Portugal</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Portugal's healthcare system ranks well internationally, with both public (SNS) and private options available. As a freelancer, you'll start with private insurance (required for visa) and can later access the public system after receiving your residence permit.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">The SNS (Public Healthcare)</h3>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">What's Covered by SNS</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>+ GP consultations (small fee ~€4-5)</li>
          <li>+ Emergency care</li>
          <li>+ Hospital treatment and surgery</li>
          <li>+ Specialist referrals</li>
          <li>+ Maternity and pediatric care</li>
          <li>+ Prescription subsidies</li>
          <li>+ Mental health services</li>
          <li>+ Chronic disease management</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-amber-200 bg-amber-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-amber-900 mb-3">SNS Challenges</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-amber-800">
          <li>• Long wait times for specialists (months)</li>
          <li>• GP appointments can take weeks</li>
          <li>• Limited English outside Lisbon/Porto</li>
          <li>• Bureaucratic registration process</li>
          <li>• Some medications may not be covered</li>
          <li>• Dental care limited (mostly private)</li>
          <li>• Quality varies by region</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">How to Register with SNS</h3>

    <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">After Getting Your Residence Permit</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Visit your local Centro de Saude (health center) with your residence permit, NIF, and proof of address. You'll be assigned a doctor and receive your numero de utente (patient number). This may take 1-2 visits and several weeks.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Using Private Healthcare</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">With private insurance, you can access clinics like Hospital da Luz, CUF, and Lusíadas immediately. No registration required—just show your insurance card. English-speaking doctors are common in Lisbon and Porto private clinics. Same-day appointments often available.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-primary-500 pl-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Emergencies</h4>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Call 112 for emergencies. Public hospital emergency rooms (Urgencias) treat everyone regardless of insurance. For non-emergency after-hours care, private hospitals have 24/7 emergency services. Keep your insurance card handy at all times.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>The hybrid approach:</strong> Most expat freelancers maintain private insurance while also registering with SNS. Use private for routine care and quick specialist access; use SNS for emergencies, major procedures, and as a backup. This provides the best of both systems.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is Portugal's D7 visa really just ~€870/month income?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes, the legal minimum is the Portuguese minimum wage—approximately €870/month in 2025. However, consulates like to see somewhat higher income or savings for a comfortable life. €1,200-1,500/month income or €10,000+ savings strengthens your application. But the threshold is genuinely low compared to Spain (€2,200) or Portugal's D8 (€3,040).
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the difference between D7 and D8 visas for freelancers?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          D7 is the "passive income" visa but has evolved to accept freelancers and remote workers. Income requirement: ~€870/month. D8 is the newer Digital Nomad Visa specifically for remote workers. Income requirement: €3,040/month. Both lead to the same residence permit and citizenship path. Most freelancers use D7 due to the lower threshold.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is SafetyWing accepted for the D7 visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Some applicants have successfully used SafetyWing for the initial visa application—Portugal is less strict than Spain. However, it's travel medical insurance, not comprehensive health coverage. For the residence permit stage and your own protection, upgrading to proper international health insurance (Cigna, Allianz) is strongly recommended.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What is the NHR tax regime and should I apply?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Non-Habitual Resident (NHR) status offers 20% flat tax on Portuguese-source income from "high value" activities (most professional work qualifies) for 10 years. You must apply within 12 months of becoming a tax resident. The benefits can be substantial—worth thousands per year. Apply immediately after getting your residence permit. Note: NHR rules changed in 2024; consult a tax advisor.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long until I can get Portuguese citizenship?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          After 5 years of legal residence, you can apply for Portuguese citizenship. You'll need to pass an A2 Portuguese language test and have no serious criminal record. Portugal allows dual citizenship—you won't need to renounce your original nationality. This is one of Europe's fastest paths to EU citizenship.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I access public healthcare with the D7 visa?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes, after receiving your residence permit, you can register at your local Centro de Saude to access the SNS (public healthcare). However, this isn't available for the visa application—you need private insurance first. Most expats maintain private insurance even after gaining SNS access for faster care and English-speaking doctors.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
